  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Task Force Sustainable Landscape Innovation</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Competing land use and resource claims by a wide variety of actors converge at the landscape level. Landscapes are therefore increasingly seen as the spatial scale on which many stakeholders, from global to local level, need to cooperate. The strategy of this Task Force is to develop and/or strengthen policy neutral platforms that bridge the intrinsic tensions between production, farmers&#x2019; livelihoods and the environment. The platforms form the basis of a new governance structure that aims to formulate management frameworks for production and natural resource management, based on pilot tested technological solutions. By bringing together regional government and sourcing companies to the negotiating table with those living in the landscape, who were previously not involved, win-win solutions can be found and tested that are supported by local people.
Over the course of 2019, we developed the Integrated Landscape Management Cycle, that brings together the key principles of the Landscape Approach in process steps. For each phase in the cycle, specific tools are available to facilitate and accelerate basic processes of integrated landscape management. 

We have invested in a number of existing and new tools to address specific elements of landscape level programming and implementation. The tools support different types of participatory assessments to engage stakeholders, generate knowledge about the landscape and help to jointly identify and prioritize interventions. One of those tools is the Landscape Governance Assessment tool developed by Tropenbos International. Landscape governance relates to how decision making addresses overlapping claims and conflicting interests in the landscape. The tool helps to assess the status of landscape governance in a participatory way around criteria such as the level of inclusive decision-making in the landscape, the culture of collaboration in the landscape and the level of coordination across landscape sectors. Based on this tool, Solidaridad piloted landscape governance assessment workshops in the Kilimanjaro Landscape and it informed us about governance challenges and possible solutions. Tools are gathered on a Landscapes Knowledge Hub, developed on the Solidaridad Intranet in 2019 to facilitate knowledge and tool sharing, and where webinars and communication is channeled among Landscape practitioners and interested colleagues.</narrative>
  </description>
